 the concept of equilibrium thermodynamics and its generalization to systems in local equilibrium. Thermodynamic fluxes are defined and caused by generalized forces. Finally, linear relations, the Onsager relations, between fluxes and forces allow for a closed description. In this way, conservation equations for mass (continuity), momentum (Euler or Navier-Stokes), and energy (temperature) are derived and solved analytically or numerically for several examples. The second part is based on the kinetic gas theory describing a classical many particle system. At the example of a perfect gas the conservation equations derived phenomenologically in the first part are thereby put on statistical grounds. The textbook addresses advanced Bachelor or Master students of physics, mechanical engineering and applied mathematics.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aBoltzmann-Gleichung. 4aKinetische Gastheorie. 4aOnsager-Beziehungen und Nichtgleichgewichtsthermodynamik. 4aStrömungsdynamik. 4aVerbreitungs- und Transportprobleme. 7aSCIENCE / Mechanics / Thermodynamics.2bisacsh  aBoltzmann equation.  aDiffusion and transport problems.  aFluid dynamics.  aKinetic gas theory.  aOnsager relations and nonequilibrium thermodynamics.0 cEPUBz97831107941990 cprintz978311079404540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311079413740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110794137423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110794137/original  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles